{"parse":{"title":"nun","pageid":41108,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Nun|nún|nùn|ñun|Nun.|ن}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|nonne}}, {{m|enm|nunne}}, from {{inh|en|ang|nunne||nun}}, from {{der|en|la-lat|nonna||nun, tutor}}, originally (along with masculine form {{m|la|nonnus||man}}) a term of address for elderly persons, perhaps from {{onomatopoeic|en|title=children's speech}}, reminiscent of {{m|en|nana}}, like {{m|en|papa}} etc. {{doublet|en|nonna}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{enPR|nŭn}}, {{IPA|en|/nʌn/}}\n* {{audio|en|En-au-nun.ogg|a=AU}}\n* {{IPA|en|/nʊn/|a=North England,Ireland}}\n* {{homophones|en|none}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ʌn|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A member of a [[Christian]] religious community of women who live by certain [[vow]]s and usually wear a [[habit]], {{lb|en|Roman Catholicism|specifically}} those living together in a [[cloister]].\n#: {{syn|en|sister|moniale|sistren|cloistress}}\n#: {{ant|en|brother|friar|monk|frater}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1988|author=w:Tsitsi Dangarembga|title=w:Nervous Conditions|publisher=Faber & Faber Limited (2021)|page=258|passage=Thus, when the '''nuns''' came to the mission and we saw that instead of murmuring soft blessings and gliding seraphically over the grass in diaphanous habits, they wore smart blouses and skirts and walked, laughed and talked in low twanging tones very much like our own American missionaries did, we were very disappointed.}}\n# {{lb|en|by extension}} A member of a similar female community in other [[confession]]s.\n#: {{ux|en|a Buddhist '''nun'''}}\n# {{lb|en|archaic|British|slang}} A [[prostitute]].<ref>{{R:Farmer|volume=5|page=76}}</ref>\n#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:prostitute}}\n#* {{RQ:Foote Lame Lover|page=12|passage=Why laſt night, as Colonel Kill'em, Sir William Weezy, Lord Frederick Foretop, and I were careleſsly ſliding the Ranelagh round, picking our teeth, after a damn'd muzzy dinner at Boodle's, who ſhould trip by but an abbeſs, well known about town, with a ſmart little '''nun''' in her ſuite.}}\n#* {{quote-book\n|en\n|year=1881\n|author=w:Pierce Egan\n|title=Life in London\n|chapter=8\n|page=205\n|url=http://archive.org/stream/tomjerrylifeinlo1881egan#page/204/mode/2up\n|passage=\"I mean to inform you,\" answered the ''Oxonian'', with a grin on his face, \"that those three nymphs, who have so much dazzled your optics, are three '''nuns''', and the plump female is ''Mother'' .... of great notoriety [...]\"\n}}\n# A kind of [[pigeon]] with the [[feather]]s on its head like the hood of a nun.\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* In [[Roman Catholicism]], a distinction is often drawn, especially by members of female [[religious order]]s, between nuns and sisters, the former being cloistered and devoted primarily to prayer, while the latter being more active, doing work such as operating hospitals, caring for the poor, or teaching.\n\n=====Hyponyms=====\n* ''See'' {{l|en|Poor Clare}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|nunate|nunation|nunbird|nunless|nunlet|nunly|nunnation|nunnish|nunship|nunsploitation|unnun|corporate nun|nun buoy|nun-coloured|nunhood|nunlike|nun-like|Nun Monkton|nun moth|nunnery|Nun of the Visitation|dry as a nun's nasty|dry as a nun's cunt|nun's thread}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{sense|member of a religious community}} {{l|en|nonnus}}\n* {{sense|prostitute}} {{l|en|abbess}},  {{l|en|abbot}}, {{l|en|Covent Garden nun}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top-see|member of a Christian religious community of women|monk}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|non}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|murgeshë|f}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|رَاهِبَة|f}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|միանձնուհի}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|monxa|f}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t|az|rahibə}}\n* Basque: {{t+|eu|moja}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|мана́шка|f}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|монахи́ня|f}}, {{t|bg|калу́герка|f}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|monja|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|修女|tr=xiūnǚ}}, {{t+|cmn|尼姑|tr=nígū}}, {{t+|cmn|姑子|tr=gūzi}}, {{t+|cmn|尼|tr=ní}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|jeptiška|f}}, {{t+|cs|řeholnice|f}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|nonne|c}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|non|f}}, (klooster-, slot-){{t+|nl|zuster|f}}\n* Erzya: {{t|myv|ськамонава}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|monaĥino}}\n* Estonian: {{t+|et|nunn}}\n* Faroese: {{t|fo|nunna|f}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|nunna}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|nonne|f}}, {{t+|fr|religieuse|f}}, {{t+|fr|bonne sœur|f}}, {{t+|fr|moniale|f}}, {{t+|fr|nonnain|f}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|madre|f}}, {{t|gl|monxa|f}}, {{t|gl|touquinegra|f}} {{qualifier|archaic}}, {{t|gl|freira|f}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|მონაზონი}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Nonne|f}}, {{t+|de|Ordensschwester|f}}, {{t|de|Klosterschwester|f}}, {{t+|de|Schwester}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|μοναχή|f}}, {{t+|el|καλόγρια|f}}\n* Hebrew: {{t|he|נְזִירָה|f|tr=nezirá}}\n* Hindi: {{t|hi|मठवासिनी|f}}, {{t+|hi|भक्तिन|f}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|apáca}}, {{t+|hu|nővér}}\n* Icelandic: {{t|is|nunna|f}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|biarawati}}, {{t+|id|suster}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|bean rialta|f}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|suora|f}}, {{t+|it|monaca|f}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|修道女|tr=しゅうどうじょ, shūdōjo}}, {{t+|ja|尼僧|tr=にそう, nisō}}, {{t+|ja|童貞|tr=dōtei}}, {{qualifier|now derogatory}} {{t+|ja|尼|tr=あま, ama}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|수녀(修女)}}, {{t+|ko|비구니(比丘尼)}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t|ky|монахиня}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|nonna|f}}, {{t|la|monacha|f}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|mūķene|f}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t|lt|vienuolė|f}}\n* Luxembourgish: {{t+|lb|Nonn|f}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|калуѓерка|f}}\n* Malay: {{t|ms|rahib perempuan}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|none}}\n* Marshallese: {{t|mh|bōjin}}\n* Mongolian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t+|mn|гэлэнмаа}}\n* Norman: {{t|nrf|nonne|f}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t|nb|nonne|m|f}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|nonne|f}}\n* Old English: {{t|ang|nunne|f}}\n* Ossetian: {{t|os|моладзан}}\n* Persian:\n*: Dari: {{t|prs|رَاهِبَه}}\n*: Iranian Persian: {{t|fa-ira|راهِبِه}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|zakonnica}}, {{t+|pl|mniszka|f}}, {{t|pl|siostra zakonna|f}}, {{t+|pl|siostra|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|freira}}, {{t+|pt|religiosa|f}}, {{t+|pt|madre|f}}, {{t+|pt|monja|f}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|călugăriță|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|мона́хиня|f}}, {{t+|ru|мона́шка|f}}\n* Sami:\n*: Skolt Sami: {{t|sms|manaših}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|cailleach dhubh|f}}, {{t|gd|bean-chràbhaidh|f}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|часна сестра|f}}, {{t|sh|калуђерица|f}}, {{t|sh|монахиња|f}}, {{t|sh|редовница|f}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|časna sestra|f}}, {{t+|sh|kaluđerica|f}}, {{t+|sh|monahinja|f}}, {{t+|sh|redovnica|f}}\n* Slovak: {{t+|sk|mníška|f}}, {{t|sk|rehoľníčka|f}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|nuna|f}}, {{t|sl|redovnica|f}}\n* Sorbian:\n*: Lower Sorbian: {{t|dsb|mnichowka|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|monja|f}}, {{t+|es|religiosa|f}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|sista}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|nunna|c}}\n* Tagalog: {{t|tl|madre}}\n* Tajik: {{t|tg|роҳиба}}\n* Tamil: {{t+|ta|துறவி}}\n* Tetun Dili: {{t|tdt|madre}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|ชี}}, {{t+|th|แม่ชี}}\n* Tibetan: {{t|bo|བཙུན་མ}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|rahibe}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|мона́хиня|f}}, {{t|uk|мона́шка|f}}, {{t|uk|черни́ця|f}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|راہِبَہ|f}}, {{t|ur|نَن|f}}\n* Uyghur: {{t|ug|راھىبە}}\n* Uzbek: {{t+|uz|rohiba}}, {{t|uz|monashka}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|xơ}} {{qualifier|Roman Catholicism}}, {{t+|vi|bà xơ}} {{qualifier|Roman Catholicism}}, {{t+|vi|nữ tu sĩ}}, {{t|vi|nữ tu}}\n* Vilamovian: {{t|wym|nunn|f}}\n* Volapük: {{qualifier|♂♀}} {{t+|vo|kleudan}}, {{qualifier|♂}} {{t+|vo|hikleudan}}, {{qualifier|♀}} {{t+|vo|jikleudan}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|lleian|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|member of a non-Christian religious community of women}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|non}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my|သီလရှင်}}, {{t+|my|ဘိက္ခုနီ}} {{qualifier|mendicant Buddhist nun}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Hokkien: {{t+|nan-hbl|尼姑|tr=nî-ko͘ / lî-ko͘}}\n* Czech: {{t|cs|mniška|f}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|monaĥino}}\n* Galician: {{t|gl|monxa|f}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|მონაზონი}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|μοναχή|f}}\n* Hindi: {{t|hi|मठवासिनी|f}}, {{t+|hi|तपस्विनी|f}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|monaca|f}}\n* Khmer: {{t+|km|ជី}}\n* Mongolian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t+|mn|гэлэнмаа}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|mniszka|f}}\n* Tamil: {{t+|ta|துறவி}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|ชี}}, {{t+|th|แม่ชี}}\n* Tibetan: {{t|bo|ཨ་ནི}}\n* Tocharian A: {{t|xto|aśi}}\n* Uyghur: {{t|ug|راھىبە}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|ni|tr=尼}} {{qualifier|Buddism}}, {{t+|vi|nữ tu sĩ|tr=女修士}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Georgian: {{t-check|ka|კუსი}}, {{t-check|ka|ყუსი}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Further reading====\n* {{pedia|Nun}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nBorrowed from the letter’s name in the respective language. {{doublet|en|nu}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{l|en|noon}}\n* {{l|en|nūn}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{enPR|nŏŏn}}, {{IPA|en|/nʊn/}} ''or'' {{enPR|no͞on}}, {{IPA|en|/nuːn/}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-nun (oo).wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ʊn|uːn|s=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# The fourteenth [[letter]] of many [[Semitic]] [[alphabet]]s or [[abjad]]s ([[Phoenician]], [[Aramaic]], [[Hebrew]], [[Syriac]], [[Arabic]] and others).\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|Semitic letter}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|نُون|m}}, {{t+|ar|ن}} {{qualifier|letter}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|nun|f}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|noen}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|nun}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|noun|m}}, {{t+|fr|nun|m}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|נון|m|tr=nun}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|نون|tr=nun}}, {{t|fa|ن}} {{qualifier|letter}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|nun}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|нун|m|n}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|nun|f|n}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|نون|f|tr=nūn}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|נון|m|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====See also====\n* [[Appendix:Hebrew alphabet]]\n\n====Further reading====\n* {{pedia|Nun (letter)}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{en-pron}}\n\n# {{pronunciation spelling of|en|nothing}}.\n\n===References===\n<references />\n* {{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}\n\n{{C|en|Hebrew letter names|Phoenician letter names}}\n{{cln|en|3-letter words|heteronyms}}\n{{C|en|Arabic letter names|Monasticism|People|Catholicism|Female people|Religious occupations}}\n\n==Asturian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{ast-pr}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|ast|la|nōn}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|ast|ñun}}\n\n====Adverb====\n{{ast-adv}}\n\n# [[not]], [[no]] (used to make negatives)\n\n=====Related terms=====\n{{col|ast|non}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Contraction====\n{{head|ast|contraction}}\n\n# [[in]] [[a]]/[[an]] (contraction of {{l|ast|en}} + {{l|ast|un}})\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:ast:DGLA}}\n* {{R:ast:DALLA}}\n\n==Azerbaijani==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|az|ar|نُون}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{az-noun}}\n\n# the Arabic letter {{lang|mul|sc=Arab|ن}} {{c|az|Arabic letter names}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{az-decl-noun|u|c}}\n\n====Further reading====\n* {{R:az:Obastan}}\n\n==Bambara==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|bm|noun|head=nún}}\n\n# {{lb|bm|anatomy}} [[nose]]\n\n===References===\n* Richard Nci Diarra, [http://bambara.org/fr/index.htm ''Lexique bambara-français-anglais''], December 13, 2010\n\n==Champenois==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|roa-cha|fro|nun|negun}}, from {{inh|roa-cha|la|nec unus}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|roa-cha|/nœ̃/}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|roa-cha|adverb}}\n\n# {{lb|roa-cha|Troyen|Langrois}} [[nobody]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:roa-cha:Daunay}}\n* {{R:roa-cha:Baudouin}}\n\n==Chiricahua==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{l|apm|non}} {{qualifier|in older Americanist literature}}\n\n===Etymology===\nCognates: Navajo {{m|nv|nooʼ}}, Western Apache {{m|apw|non}}, {{m|apw|noi}}, Plains Apache {{m|apk|nǫǫ}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|apm|/nòn/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|apm|noun}}\n\n# [[grave]], [[burial]] place\n# [[cache]]\n\n==Chuj==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|cac|noun}}\n\n# [[parent]]\n\n==Esperanto==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|eo|de|nun}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{eo-pr|a=LL-Q143 (epo)-Lepticed7-nun.wav;LL-Q143 (epo)-Robin van der Vliet-nun.wav}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{eo-head}}\n\n# [[now]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4\n|eo|{{l|eo|ĝisnuna|t=(up) until now}}\n|nuna\n|nune\n|nuntempe\n}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:eo:PIV 2020}}\n* {{R:eo:ReVo}}\n\n{{eo BRO|1}}\n\n==Fala==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|fax|roa-opt|non}}, from {{inh|fax|la|nōn||not}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{fax-pr}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|fax|adverb}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|fax|non|t=no, not}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:fax:Diccionariu|211}}\n\n==Finnish==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|fi|phn|}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{fi-p}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fi-noun}}\n\n# [[#English|nun]] {{gloss|fourteenth letter of the Hebrew and Phoenician scripts and the Northwest Semitic abjad}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{fi-decl-risti|nun|||a|i=0}}\n\n{{C|fi|Hebrew letter names|Phoenician letter names}}\n\n==Galician==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{gl-pr}}\n* {{hyph|gl|nun}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom contraction of preposition {{m|gl|en||in}} + masculine article {{m|gl|un||a, one}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|gl|num||reinteg}}\n\n====Contraction====\n{{head|gl|contraction|g=m|feminine|nunha|masculine plural|nuns|feminine plural|nunhas}}\n\n# [[in]] [[a]], in [[one]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\nProbably from or under influence of {{der|gl|ast|nun}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|gl|num}}\n\n====Adverb====\n{{gl-adv}}\n\n# {{lb|gl|Galician-Asturian}} [[not]]\n#* {{quote-book|gl|title=Boal y su Concejo|year=1898|author=Acevedo Huelves|page=61|passage=En Llanteiro '''nun''' hay mozas, en Mezà todas son veyas, en Miñagon milindrosas y en Serandías a fror d'ellas.|translation=In Llanteiro there are '''no''' girls, in Mezá they are all old, in Miñagón [they are] finicky and in Serandías [they are] the cream of the crop.}}\n#* {{quote-book|gl|title=El Franco y su Concejo|year=1898|author=Marcelino Fernández Fernández|page=112|passage=As cuitas ayías, '''num''' me quitan dormir. / Condo Dios '''nun''' quer, os Santos '''nun''' poden|translation=Other people's troubles '''don't''' keep me up at night / When God '''doesn't''' want [it], the Saints can'''not'''}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:gl:DDLG|num}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:gl:DRAG}}\n\n==German==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|de|/nuːn/}}\n* {{audio|de|De-nun.ogg}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{der|de|gmh|nu|nu, nū}}, {{m|gmh|nuo}} with a secondary final ''-n'', already occasionally in {{inh|de|gmh|nuon}}, from {{inh|de|goh|nu}}, from {{inh|de|gmw-pro|*nū}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|de|nu||colloquial; otherwise archaic}}\n\n====Adverb====\n{{de-adv}}\n\n# [[now]], at this moment\n# [[now]], [[then]]; {{n-g|expressing a logical or temporal consequence}}\n#: {{ux|de|Wir haben abgewaschen, '''nun''' müssen wir noch abtrocknen.|We've washed up, '''now''' we must dry [the dishes].}}\n#: {{ux|de|Was bedeuten '''nun''' die geschilderten Entwicklungen für unser Land?|'''Now''' what do the aforementioned developments mean for our country?}}\n# {{n-g|unstressed and expletive, used for minor emphasis}}\n#: {{ux|de|Was soll das '''nun''' heißen?|What's that supposed to mean '''now'''?}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* Although the adverb is similar and akin to English “now”, German ''nun'' is not commonly used in a strictly temporal sense, meaning “at this moment”. For that, see {{m|de|jetzt}}.\n\n====Interjection====\n{{head|de|interjection}}\n\n# [[now]], [[well]], [[so]]\n#: {{ux|de|'''Nun''', das ist eine schwierige Frage.|'''Well''', that's a tough question.}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{clipping|de|nun dass,[[nun]] [[da]]}}.\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{head|de|conjunction}}\n\n# {{tlb|de|literary|_|or|_|dated|_|colloquial}} [[now that]], given that it has occurred that the circumstances do not withstand that …\n\n==Hausa==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{bor|ha|ar|نُون}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ha-IPA|nun}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{ha-noun|f|nun}}\n\n# {{l|en|nun}} {{gl|letter of the Arabic alphabet}}\n\n{{C|ha|Arabic letter names}}\n\n==Ido==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{io-bor|eo=nun|de=nun}} Originally replaced with {{m|io|nunk}}, it was eventually taken back.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{io-IPA}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{io-adv}}\n\n# {{l|en|now}}, {{l|en|at present}}, at {{l|en|this time}}\n#: {{syn|io|nunk<qq:archaic>}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col2|io\n| nuna<t:present, actual, current, now occurring>\n| nuntempa<t:present day, time>\n| nuntempe<t:at the present time>\n| nuna stando<t:the existing condition, status quo>\n| nuna evento<t:a present, current event>\n| nun kande<t:now when, now that>\n}}\n\n==Italian==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|it|he|נו״ן|tr=nun}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{it-pr}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{it-noun|f|#}}\n\n# {{l|it|nun}}, {{n-g|specifically}}:\n## {{n-g|the name of the [[Appendix:Phoenician script|Phoenician-script]] letter}} '''[[𐤍]]'''\n## {{n-g|the name of the [[Appendix:Hebrew script|Hebrew-script]] letter}} '''[[נ]]'''/'''[[ן]]'''\n## {{n-g|the name of the [[Appendix:Arabic script|Arabic-script]] letter}} '''[[ن]]'''\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|it|adv}}\n\n# {{tlb|it|Romanesco|Tuscan|Southern Italian}} {{altform|it|non}}\n\n{{C|it|Arabic letter names|Hebrew letter names|Phoenician letter names}}\n\n==Jebero==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|jeb|noun}}\n\n# [[canoe]]\n\n==Lombard==\n\n===Etymology===\nAkin to {{cog|it|noi}}, from Latin ''[[nos]]''.\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|lmo|pronoun}}\n\n# [[we]]\n\n==Lower Tanana==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|taa|ath-pro|*naˑn}}.\n\n===Root===\n{{head|taa|root}}\n\n# to [[drink]]\n\n====Stem set====\n{{aht-stem-set-header}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row|dur|nunh|nun'|nuɬ|nun'}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row2|mom|{{l|taa|nuyh}}|{{l|taa|nunh}}|{{l|taa|nuɬ}}|—}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row|cust|nuyh|nuyh|nuyh|nuyh}}\n{{aht-stem-set-footer}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col2|taa\n|edenunh,yedenunh<t:he/she is drinking it>\n|ch'enodenuyh<t:he/she customarily gets drunk>\n|ch'enunh<t:drinking>\n|ch'edenunhde<t:bar>\n}}\n\n===References===\n* {{Kari24|page=337}}\n\n==Mandarin==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{cmn-pinyin|notr=1}}\n\n# {{nonstandard spelling of|cmn|sc=Latn|nún}}\n# {{nonstandard spelling of|cmn|sc=Latn|nùn}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* {{cmn-toneless-note}}\n\n==Mirandese==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{mwl-pr}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{af|mwl|an<t:in>|un<t:a><pos:masculine singular indefinite article>}}.\n\n====Contraction====\n{{head|mwl|contractions|g=m-p|plural|nuns|feminine|nũa|feminine plural|nũas}}\n\n# [[in]] [[a]], [[in]] [[some]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Adverb====\n{{head|mwl|adverb}}\n\n# {{altform|mwl|nó|t=no, not}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\nUsed before verb forms, as English not.\n\n===References===\n* {{R:mwl:PVMP|364}}\n\n==Old French==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nSee {{m|fro|nom}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{fro-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|fro|Anglo-Norman}} {{alternative form of|fro|nom}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nReduced form of {{m|fro|negun}}.\n\n====Adjective====\n{{fro-adj}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|fro|negun}}\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|fro|pronoun}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|fro|negun}}\n\n==Rohingya==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{q|Arabic}} {{l|rhg|نٌ}}, {{l|rhg|نُنۡ}}\n* {{q|Bengali}} {{l|rhg|নুন}}\n* {{q|Myanmar}} {{l|rhg|နုန်}}\n* {{q|Hanifi}} {{l|rhg|𐴕𐴟𐴕}}\n\n===Etymology===\nCompare {{cog|bn|নুন}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|rhg|[nun]}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|rhg|noun}}\n\n# [[salt]]\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|rhg|nomok}}\n\n==Romanian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|ro|la-lat|nonnus}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{ro-noun|m|nuni|f=nună}}\n\n# the [[godfather]] at a [[wedding]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{ro-noun-m|def=nunul}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|ro|naș}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|ro|nuntă}}\n\n==Sarawak Malay==\n\n===Etymology===\nRelated to {{m+|map-pro|*(na-)nu}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|poz-sml|/nun/}}\n\n===Determiner===\n{{head|poz-sml|determiner}}\n\n# [[distant]] {{gl|far from the speaker}} determiner\n#: {{ant|poz-sml|tok}}\n#: {{ux|poz-sml|Rami urang sik suka ompuan '''nun'''.|A lot of people don't like '''that''' woman (over there).}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|poz-sml|sinun}} {{gl|yonder}}\n\n==Sicilian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{l|scn|non}}, {{l|scn|unn}}, {{l|scn|'un}}, {{l|scn|nn'}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|scn|la|nōn}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|scn|/nun/|[nun]|[un]|[n]}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|scn|adverb}}\n\n# [[not]]\n\n==Sumerian==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{sux-rom}}\n\n# {{romanization of|sux|𒉣|tr=nun}}\n\n==Talysh==\n\n===Etymology===\nCognate with {{cog|fa|نان|tr=nân}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|tly|noun}}\n\n# [[bread]]\n\n{{C|tly|Breads}}\n\n==Tat==\n\n===Etymology===\nAkin to {{cog|fa|نان|tr=nân|t=bread}}, see there for more.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|ttt|noun}}\n\n# [[bread]]\n\n==Turkish==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|tr|ota|نون|tr=nûn}}, from {{der|tr|ar|نُون}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|tr|noun}}\n\n# Letter of the Arabic alphabet: {{lang|mul|sc=Arab|ن}}\n#* Previous: {{l|mul|sc=Arab|م}}\n#* Next: {{l|mul|sc=Arab|و}}\n\n{{C|tr|Arabic letter names}}\n\n==Uzbek==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|uz|ar|نُون}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{uz-noun}}\n\n# the Arabic letter {{lang|mul|sc=Arab|ن}} {{c|uz|Arabic letter names}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{uz-decl-noun}}\n\n==Volapük==\n\n===Noun===\n{{vo-noun}}\n\n# [[message]]\n#* {{quote-journal|vo|year=1946|author=|title=Nuns|journal=Volapükagased pro Nedänapükans|pages=34|passage=Ko lied gretik egetobs '''nuni''', das vomül: ‚Maria Willebrand’ in ‚Warendorf’ e söl: ‚Ing. Paul Tarnow’ in ‚Düsseldorf-Oberkassel’ edeadons sekü krigaduns.|t=With great regret we have received the '''news''' that Miss Maria Willebrand of Warendorf and Mr. ing. Paul Tarnow of Düsseldorf-Oberkassel have died as a result of war action.}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{vo-decl-noun}}\n\n==Wolof==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{l|wo|ñun}} {{q|used alongside \"nun\" in Urban Wolof}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|wo|pronoun}}\n\n# [[we]] {{gloss|first-person plural subject pronoun}}\n\n====See also====\n{{wo-personal pronouns}}\n\n==Zazaki==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|zza|[ˈnun]}}\n* {{hyphenation|zza|nun}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{zza-noun|g=m}}\n\n# {{alt form|zza|nan}}"}}